==In popular culture==
* ''I Want to Thank My Brain For Remembering Me'', by Jimmy Breslin - former Pulitzer Prize winner's book on his treatment at the BNI For a brain aneurysm<ref name=book>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/Want-Thank-My-Brain-Remembering/dp/0316118796 |title=Jimmy Brezler |work= |accessdate=}}</ref>

* ''[[The Vow (2012 film)|The Vow]]'' (2012) - movie based on the real story of patient treated at the BNI who woke up with severe memory loss after a TBI

*[[Pam Reynolds case]] - notable [[standstill operation]] performed by [[Robert F. Spetzler]] that took place at the Institute in 1991 in which a 35-year old American woman was induced into [[clinically dead|clinical death]] for the removal of a large aneurysm in her brain, later to accurately recall the events after claiming to have had a [[near-death experience]]<ref>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WNbdUEqDB-k</ref>

* [[Ronan (song)]] - song by Taylor Swift on Ronan Thompson, a young boy with neuroblastoma treated at the BNI

* The Healing Blade - written by Edward J. Sylvester, the book covers the history of the BNI and the standstill procedure popularized by Robert Spetzler

